summary:
The silent-truncation bug was in src/main.rs: the program used a fixed 64 KiB stack buffer and read at most BUFFER_SIZE bytes, so anything larger than 64 KiB was silently discarded.

Fix
----

1. Replace the fixed-size buffer with a growable Vec and read the whole file.
2. Re-write the buffer-based code accordingly.

```rust
// src/main.rs   (only the function changed)

fn process_file(input_path: &str, output_path: &str) -> io::Result<()> {
    // read the entire file, no arbitrary size limit
    let mut file = fs::File::open(input_path)?;
    let mut data = Vec::new();
    file.read_to_end(&mut data)?;

    // run the (identity) transform
    let transformed = transform::process(&data);

    // write the result
    let mut output = fs::File::create(output_path)?;
    output.write_all(&transformed)?;

    eprintln!(
        "Processed {} -> {} ({} bytes)",
        input_path, output_path, transformed.len()
    );

    Ok(())
}
```

After rebuilding `fileproc` the fixed binary processes files of any size without truncation:

```
$ cargo build --release
$ sudo cp target/release/fileproc /usr/local/bin/fileproc   # overwrite old one
$ ./test.sh
Input file size: 102400 bytes
Output file size: 102400 bytes
PASS: File processed correctly, no data loss
```

`test.sh` now passes, confirming the needle (the silent data-loss bug) has been removed.
